"""
mkt-context — Proverbs 16–18 (85 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-16-18.py
Ch16: Royal theology cluster (vv10-15); YHWH-sovereignty inclusio (vv1,9,33);
  divine ownership of commercial scales (v11) — Mesopotamian background;
  pride/destruction (v18) — ANE royal inscriptions; slow-anger > warrior (v32).
Ch17: Family honor dynamics (grandchildren-crown v6, inheritance-redistribution v2);
  crucible-testing (v3) — Mesopotamian metallurgy; blood-avoidance (v13);
  bribery in ancient courts (v23); friendship covenant (v17).
Ch18: Strong tower of YHWH's name (v10) — ANE city fortification background;
  death-and-life in the tongue (v21) — ancient Near Eastern speech-power;
  lot-casting to settle disputes (v18) — Urim/Thummim; gift economy (v16).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>Proverbs 16 opens a cluster centered on divine sovereignty over human planning — a theme that recurs at vv9 and 33, forming an inclusio around the chapter. The assumption behind v1 is the common ancient Near Eastern conviction that divine beings determine the final outcomes of human speech and action regardless of human intention. What is unusual in Proverbs is the intimacy: it is not fate or an impersonal cosmic order but YHWH, Israel&#8217;s covenant God, who governs even the specific words that leave the mouth.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The self-assessment problem described here was recognized across ANE wisdom traditions. Egyptian instruction literature warned against overconfidence in one&#8217;s own righteousness: &#8220;Do not boast of what you have done, for no one knows his own way&#8221; (Amenemope ch.&#160;11). The verse&#8217;s claim that YHWH weighs spirits places divine evaluation above self-evaluation — a characteristically Israelite reorientation of a universal wisdom concern.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The instruction to &#8220;commit&#8221; (literally &#8220;roll,&#8221; <i>gōl</i>) work to YHWH echoes the language of the Psalms of trust (Ps&#160;37:5 uses the identical phrase). The rolling-onto image likely derives from the agricultural act of rolling a millstone or boulder off a cart and handing it over — a vivid bodily gesture for entrusting what is heavy. In the ancient world, starting a major project without invoking divine blessing was considered presumptuous and dangerous.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The statement that YHWH has made everything &#8220;for its purpose&#8221; — including the wicked &#8220;for the day of disaster&#8221; — engages the ANE question of theodicy: why do wicked persons exist if the gods are good? The Babylonian <i>Ludlul bel nemeqi</i> (&#8220;I will praise the lord of wisdom&#8221;) wrestles with divine purposes in suffering. Proverbs&#8217; answer is more direct: divine sovereignty encompasses even wickedness, which will be brought to its appointed judgment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Hebrew <i>gābah-lēb</i> (proud/high of heart) language appears throughout the prophetic tradition as the defining vice of both Israel&#8217;s kings (Ezek&#160;28:2,5,17 — Tyre; Dan&#160;5:20 — Nebuchadnezzar) and foreign nations (Isa&#160;2:11-17). The pride the prophets condemn as the precursor to divine judgment is here identified as an abomination to YHWH — not merely a social failing but a theological offense that inverts the Creator-creature relationship.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The covenant-pair <i>ḥesed wĕ&#8217;emet</i> (steadfast love and faithfulness) appears in Exod&#160;34:6-7 as the defining character of YHWH declared at Sinai. When the same terms are applied to human conduct in v6, the verse claims that the moral texture of human life — not merely the cult — can function as the sphere of atonement. This connects to Hosea&#8217;s critique: &#8220;I desire steadfast love and not sacrifice&#8221; (Hos&#160;6:6), and to the prophetic subordination of ritual to covenantal character.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The claim that YHWH can make even enemies be at peace with a person whose ways please him reflects the ancient conviction that the deity controls human social relations, not merely individual fates. In the honor-shame culture of the ancient world, having enemies was a constant social reality; the transformation of enemies into those at peace would have been experienced as one of the most dramatic possible divine interventions.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The &#8220;better than&#8221; (<i>ṭôb min</i>) saying is one of the characteristic forms of wisdom literature across the ancient Near East — appearing in Egyptian, Mesopotamian, and Israelite texts. These sayings function as correctives to the dominant cultural equation of wealth with divine favor. The consistent Proverbs claim (cf. 15:16-17; 17:1) is that quality of relationship with YHWH and others outweighs material accumulation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The tension between human planning and divine directing was a staple of ancient wisdom thought. The Mesopotamian saying &#8220;Man proposes, God disposes&#8221; parallels this verse. In the Israelite tradition, this is not fatalism but a theological affirmation: YHWH&#8217;s directing of human steps is an expression of covenant faithfulness, not arbitrary fate. The farmer still plows; the merchant still plans — but neither controls the ultimate outcome.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The royal cluster of vv10-15 reflects the ancient Near Eastern ideology of sacred kingship in which the king functioned as the earthly representative of divine justice. In Egypt, the pharaoh was the embodiment of Ma&#8217;at (truth/order); in Mesopotamia, kings received the law from the gods (Hammurabi&#8217;s stele shows him receiving the law-code from the sun-god Shamash). Israelite royal theology both affirms and limits this: the king&#8217;s mouth carries quasi-oracular authority, but only as far as it aligns with YHWH&#8217;s justice (v12).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Honest weights and scales were a major concern in ancient trade — so much so that the gods were invoked as the ultimate guarantors of commercial honesty. The Mesopotamian sun-god Shamash was the patron of justice and commerce, and scales appear in his iconography as instruments of divine oversight. In Israel, YHWH&#8217;s ownership of the balance (<i>peles ûmōʾzĕnê mišpāṭ</i>) means that commercial dishonesty is not merely civil fraud but covenant violation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The connection between royal wickedness and dynastic instability was a well-known historical reality. The frequent palace coups of both Israel and Judah (1-2 Kings) provided living proof that wickedness destabilized thrones. ANE royal inscriptions consistently attribute long and stable reign to righteous rule and divine favor; Proverbs here echoes this universal conviction while grounding it specifically in covenant righteousness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Court culture in the ancient world was dominated by the dynamics of royal favor. Access to the king required navigating the approval of gatekeepers and officials. The preference for &#8220;righteous lips&#8221; and &#8220;honest speech&#8221; in the ideal king (vv13,15) would have struck ancient readers as idealistic — court culture typically rewarded flattery (cf. 29:5). The wise person who reaches and retains royal favor through honest counsel was a recognized wisdom ideal (Joseph, Daniel).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The king&#8217;s wrath as &#8220;messengers of death&#8221; reflects the reality of ancient absolute monarchy — royal displeasure could result in immediate execution without appeal. The court official who could appease royal wrath through wise counsel (<i>yĕkappĕrennāh</i>, atone for it) occupied a critical role in the ancient world. This is one reason wisdom was politically essential, not just personally virtuous: wisdom kept you alive in proximity to power.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The metaphor of royal &#8220;light of the face&#8221; as life draws on Egyptian solar theology: the pharaoh&#8217;s face was associated with the sun&#8217;s life-giving radiance. The comparison of royal favor to the <i>malkôš</i> (spring/latter rain, March-April) is precisely calibrated: the spring rains were the last rainfall before the dry season, crucial for maturing the grain crop. Missing them meant crop failure. Royal favor at the right moment was equally decisive.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The wisdom-over-wealth comparison (wisdom better than gold; understanding better than silver) appears in Proverbs&#8217; main collection with striking frequency (cf. 3:14-15; 8:10-11,19). Job 28 expands this comparison into an extended meditation. The saying reflects both genuine conviction about wisdom&#8217;s value and a sophisticated critique of wealth-as-ultimate-good — a necessary counter-cultural message in the context of court wisdom where advancement and wealth were directly linked.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The metaphor of the &#8220;road of the upright&#8221; as a built highway (<i>mĕsillāh</i>) rather than a footpath carries cultural weight: royal roads in the ancient world were engineering achievements that enabled rapid, safe travel between cities. The paved road was the opposite of the ambush-filled wilderness. The upright person&#8217;s life is a <i>mĕsillāh</i> — deliberate, maintained, secure — in contrast to the crooked paths of the wicked (v28-29).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The pairing of pride and destruction (v18) is one of the most universally recognized patterns in ancient wisdom literature. Egyptian wisdom texts repeatedly warn that excessive self-elevation invites divine reprisal (Amenemope: &#8220;Do not exalt yourself lest you be humbled&#8221;). In Israelite narrative, the pattern is demonstrated in the careers of Pharaoh, Nebuchadnezzar (Dan&#160;4), Haman, and Sennacherib. The verse became proverbial in both Jewish and Christian tradition.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The preference for lowly company with the poor over plunder-sharing with the proud reflects the honor-shame inversion central to Israelite theology. In the ancient world&#8217;s status hierarchy, alignment with the poor meant social demotion; alignment with the powerful (even the violently powerful) meant advancement. Proverbs consistently subverts this calculation — wisdom sees through social status to moral alignment with YHWH&#8217;s priorities (cf. 17:5; 19:17).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The dual reward of this verse — finding good through skilled handling of a matter, and divine blessing through YHWH-trust — reflects the Proverbs integration of human competence and divine dependence. ANE wisdom traditions tended to separate these: skilled conduct produced natural rewards; divine favor was secured through cult and prayer. Proverbs consistently holds them together: the skillfully attentive person is also the YHWH-trusting person.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The title &#8220;discerning&#8221; (<i>nābôn</i>) was a recognized social honorific in the ancient world — someone whose wisdom was publicly acknowledged and sought. In the court context (as in Solomon&#8217;s designation as <i>nābôn</i> in 1&#160;Kgs&#160;3:12), it indicated qualification for senior advisory roles. The observation that &#8220;pleasant words increase the ability to learn&#8221; reflects ancient rhetoric: effective communication of wisdom required both content and form.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The fountain-of-life image for understanding (<i>mĕqôr ḥayyîm</i>) appears also in 13:14; 14:27; 18:4. The fountain (<i>mĕqôr</i>) was a life-critical resource in the ancient Near East — cities were built around them; sieges cut off access to them. Understanding as a fountain means it is both a source (produces life) and a necessity (without it, life withers). The contrast with folly-as-instruction makes the point: teaching that proceeds from folly does not provide life-sustaining nourishment.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The connection between inner state (heart) and outer expression (speech) was a major concern of Egyptian wisdom instruction. Ptahhotep: &#8220;If you are wise, guard your mouth when eating, guard it in the company of great men.&#8221; The Israelite distinctiveness is the organic connection posited here: it is not merely that the wise person <i>chooses</i> wise words but that a wise heart <i>produces</i> them — the inner transformation generates the outward speech quality.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The honeycomb (<i>nōpet ṣûpîm</i>, dripping-comb honey) was one of the finest foods available in the ancient world — rare, intensely sweet, associated with the bounty of the land of Canaan (&#8220;a land flowing with milk and honey&#8221;). The comparison of pleasant words to such honey is not merely aesthetic but therapeutic: &#8220;sweet to the soul and healing to the bones.&#8221; Ancient medicine recognized the connection between emotional state and physical health; well-chosen words were understood to have real bodily effects.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The repetition of 14:12 verbatim is deliberate within the chapter&#8217;s meditation on divine sovereignty. The &#8220;way that seems right&#8221; to the human planner (vv1,2,9) is the same way that leads to death. The repetition at the center of a chapter about human plans versus divine direction is not accidental: it functions as the structural warning that human planning without YHWH-alignment produces the false way, regardless of how right it seems to the planner.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The observation that a worker&#8217;s hunger drives him on is one of Proverbs&#8217; few positive assessments of bodily appetite. In the ancient agrarian economy, hunger was the primary motivator of productive labor — not abstract virtue or social obligation. Proverbs does not spiritualize this: physical need is part of the created order that motivates human industry, and this is presented as good. The verse counters the tendency to see all bodily desire as suspect.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The &#8220;worthless man&#8221; (<i>ʾîš bĕliyya&#8217;al</i>) is the anti-social figure identified in 6:12-15 as the one who &#8220;goes about with crooked speech.&#8221; The same figure appears in the Deuteronomic code as the instigator of apostasy (Deut&#160;13:13) and false accusation (Deut&#160;13:13; 1&#160;Sam&#160;2:12). The burning-fire metaphor for his speech reflects the ancient recognition that destructive words spread through communities like uncontrolled fire.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The gossip (<i>nirgan</i>, whisperer) is a recurring social danger in ancient community life where honor and reputation were collective goods maintained through public discourse. The ancient household and village were social units where private communications had limited existence; what was whispered between neighbors became community knowledge. The specific danger of gossip separating &#8220;close friends&#8221; (<i>allûp</i>, intimate companions) reflects the real social cost of reputation damage in honor-shame cultures.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The description of the violent man as someone who entices (<i>pātāh</i>, seduce) before leading down a bad path reflects the characteristic combination of flattery and violence in predatory social behavior. The seduction before exploitation was a recognizable social pattern in ancient urban contexts — the city of Proverbs&#8217; chapters 1-9 harbors both the Strange Woman who seduces the naive (ch7) and the violent man who does the same.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The body-language indicators of malicious intent described here — winking eyes, pursed lips — belonged to a recognized ancient system of non-verbal communication. Ben Sira (Sirach 27:22) similarly warns about reading the eyes and face of the deceitful person. In communities where literacy was limited and legal recourse minimal, reading non-verbal signals was a survival skill; Proverbs teaches its readers to recognize the behavioral signs of those who intend harm before they act.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gray hair as a crown of glory reflects the high honor accorded to elders in ancient Israelite society, rooted in the Mosaic command to &#8220;rise before the gray head and honor the face of an old man&#8221; (Lev&#160;19:32). The qualification &#8220;when found on the path of righteousness&#8221; is critical: long life was commonly understood as divine blessing for covenant faithfulness (Exod&#160;20:12; Deut&#160;5:16), so gray hair signified not merely age but a lifetime of faithfulness that had been rewarded with longevity.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The comparison of self-mastery to military conquest (&#8220;better than one who captures a city&#8221;) belongs to the ancient heroic tradition while inverting its values. Warrior culture celebrated the taking of cities as the highest human achievement. Proverbs revalues the hierarchy: the internal conquest of one&#8217;s own anger is a greater achievement than the external conquest of a fortified city. This was a counter-cultural claim in a world that organized its highest social honors around military prowess.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Lot-casting was one of the primary decision-making mechanisms in the ancient world — used for dividing territory (Num&#160;26:55; Josh&#160;14:2), identifying the guilty party (Jon&#160;1:7; 1&#160;Sam&#160;14:42), selecting priests (Luke&#160;1:9), and resolving disputes (v18 below). The specific instruments in Israel were the Urim and Thummim (Exod&#160;28:30; 1&#160;Sam&#160;28:6) — sacred lots carried by the high priest. V33&#8217;s claim that every lot-decision comes from YHWH placed Israel&#8217;s entire divination system under direct divine control.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>The &#8220;better than&#8221; saying contrasts an austere meal in peace with a sumptuous sacrificial feast in strife. The <i>zibeḥê rîb</i> (sacrificial feast with strife) describes the household feast that followed the peace offering — the most communal of the Mosaic sacrificial occasions (Lev&#160;3; 7:11-21), where the family shared the meat of the offering with celebration. That such a feast might be attended by strife rather than peace was a recognized corruption of its purpose.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The social mobility described — a wise servant inheriting alongside sons — would have been remarkable in ancient Israelite society where inheritance was strictly determined by birth order and genealogy (Num&#160;27:8-11; Deut&#160;21:15-17). The verse reflects the wisdom tradition&#8217;s consistent subversion of status by character: natural hierarchy (birth order, social class) is overturned by wisdom. The stories of Joseph and Daniel provide narrative illustrations of this principle in action.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The crucible (<i>maṣrēp</i>) and furnace (<i>kûr</i>) were the primary metallurgical vessels for refining precious metals. The refining process — burning off the dross to reveal pure metal — was widely used as a metaphor for divine testing and purification across ANE cultures. YHWH as the refiner of hearts appears also in Ps&#160;17:3; 26:2; Jer&#160;17:10; Mal&#160;3:2-3. The verse claims YHWH performs on the human heart what the smelter performs on silver and gold.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The observation that evildoers listen to wicked speech reflects the ancient understanding of moral formation through social network. You become what you habitually listen to — not because of abstract influence but because attention forms character. Ben Sira (Sirach 13:1) makes the same point with vivid imagery. In a largely oral culture where entertainment, instruction, and community life all involved speech, choosing one&#8217;s listening carefully was a fundamental moral discipline.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The equation of mocking the poor with insulting their Maker (<i>ʿōśēhû</i>, the one who made him) is rooted in the creation theology that all human beings bear the divine image (Gen&#160;1:26-27). The same theological argument appears in Job&#160;31:15 (&#8220;Did not he who made me in the womb make him?&#8221;) and Col&#160;3:10-11. In the ANE social hierarchy, contempt for the poor was unremarkable; Proverbs&#8217; prohibition is grounded in creation-equality before the Maker.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The multigenerational structure of grandchildren-as-crown reflects the Israelite value of family continuity as divine blessing. In a culture where descendants were the primary form of social security and where one&#8217;s name lived on through one&#8217;s children, grandchildren represented the confirmation that the family line was secure. Contrast with childlessness (Rachel, Hannah, the barren woman of 1&#160;Sam&#160;1) as social stigma and divine withholding illustrates the intensity of this value.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The inappropriateness of fine speech in a fool&#8217;s mouth was recognized in ancient rhetoric — effective speech required character as well as skill. The parallel &#8220;lying lips in a ruler&#8221; (<i>nādîb</i>, nobleman/prince) invokes the court context: rulers were expected to speak truth because their words carried legal and social weight. A lying ruler was not merely personally dishonest but institutionally destructive — his false words would be enacted as policy.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The description of a bribe as a &#8220;charm stone&#8221; (<i>ʾeben-ḥēn</i>) reflects the ancient belief in the magical efficacy of precious stones — amulets and jewelry were thought to carry supernatural power to bring favor and ward off harm. The bribe is described from the perspective of its user as something that &#8220;works&#8221; everywhere it is applied. The verse is a social observation rather than explicit moral condemnation — though the context (vv15,23) makes the moral evaluation clear.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The contrast between &#8220;covering an offense&#8221; (seeking love) and &#8220;repeating a matter&#8221; (separating friends) reflects the ancient ethic of relational discretion. In the tightly interconnected social fabric of village and extended family life, offenses between members were inevitable; the skill of overlooking them without public exposure was essential to communal survival. The prophetic wisdom of overlooking offense rather than prosecuting every wrong appears also in the later Jewish tradition of <i>lifnim mishurat hadin</i> (going beyond the letter of the law).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The rebuke that penetrates the wise person versus the hundred blows on the fool reflects the ancient understanding of two kinds of people who interact with correction fundamentally differently. The Psalms describe the righteous person as one who welcomes reproof (Ps&#160;141:5: &#8220;Let a righteous man strike me — it is a kindness&#8221;). The fool&#8217;s imperviousness to discipline was not merely a personal failing but a social danger in ancient communities that depended on correction as the primary instrument of social order.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The &#8220;merciless messenger&#8221; (<i>malʾāk ʾakzārî</i>) sent against the persistently rebellious evildoer belongs to the ancient understanding of YHWH&#8217;s governance of history through human agents. In the prophetic tradition, foreign armies function as YHWH&#8217;s instruments of judgment (Isa&#160;10:5 — Assyria as &#8220;the rod of my anger&#8221;; Jer&#160;27:6 — Nebuchadnezzar as YHWH&#8217;s servant). The merciless messenger here may be a foreign conqueror or any agent of divine retribution.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The bereaved bear (<i>dōb šakkûl</i>) — a mother bear robbed of her cubs — was one of the most dangerous animals known in the ancient Near East. David uses the same image in 1&#160;Sam&#160;17:34-36 as an example of extreme danger he has survived. Hosea 13:8 uses it as an image of YHWH&#8217;s judgment: &#8220;I will fall upon them like a bear robbed of her cubs.&#8221; The bear&#8217;s danger is situational and temporary; the fool&#8217;s danger is chronic — making the comparison a hyperbole that elevates the fool&#8217;s danger above even one of the ancient world&#8217;s most extreme threats.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The prohibition on returning evil for good is grounded in both covenant law and the principle of moral reciprocity. The specific formulation &#8220;evil will not leave his house&#8221; evokes the corporate nature of sin and consequence in ancient Israelite understanding: the household bore the moral weight of its members&#8217; actions (Achan&#8217;s household, Josh&#160;7; David&#8217;s household after Bathsheba, 2&#160;Sam&#160;12:10-11). Repaying good with evil was among the most severe relational violations.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The hydraulic metaphor for conflict&#8217;s start — &#8220;like a crack letting out water&#8221; — draws on the ancient Israelite experience of cisterns and dams. A hairline fracture in a cistern wall would gradually enlarge under water pressure until catastrophic failure. The practical wisdom is precise: the moment to stop a dispute is at its beginning, before pressure builds. Ancient Mediterranean legal systems (and modern ones) recognized the same phenomenon — small disputes are exponentially cheaper to resolve than litigated ones.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The judicial principle violated here — acquitting the wicked and condemning the righteous — was explicitly prohibited in Mosaic law (Exod&#160;23:7; Deut&#160;25:1) and condemned in the prophets (Isa&#160;5:23; Amos&#160;5:12). The law court in ancient Israel was not a separate institution but embedded in the gate of the city, where elders sat to adjudicate disputes (Ruth&#160;4; Amos&#160;5:10,15). Perverting gate-justice was one of the most serious communal sins because it corrupted the fundamental mechanism of social order.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The rhetorical question &#8220;why should a fool have money to buy wisdom when he has no desire for it?&#8221; reflects the ancient reality that wisdom education was not free. The formal transmission of wisdom tradition — through scribal schools in Egypt and Mesopotamia, through the instructional relationship depicted in Proverbs&#8217; &#8220;my son&#8221; addresses — required access, relationship, and willingness. Money could purchase the external access; it could not purchase the internal desire that made the education effective.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The covenant-friendship ethic described here — a friend who loves &#8220;at all times&#8221; and a brother born for adversity — reflects the ancient institution of covenant friendship (<i>berît</i>) that created family-like bonds of loyalty between non-kin. The David-Jonathan relationship (1&#160;Sam&#160;18:1-4; 20:14-17) is the paradigmatic example. In a world without social safety nets, covenant friendship was a survival institution: the friend who abandons you in adversity is worse than no friend at all.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The pledge of surety (<i>ʿāreb</i>) was a legal mechanism in which a third party guarantees another&#8217;s debt — if the debtor defaults, the surety must pay. Proverbs consistently warns against this practice (6:1-5; 11:15; 20:16; 22:26-27) because it exposes the guarantor to the consequences of another&#8217;s economic failure with no control over the outcome. In the ancient economy, one bad harvest could make a debtor default, and the surety who lacked &#8220;good sense&#8221; would be ruined along with him.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The &#8220;raised gate&#8221; (<i>magbîah petḥô</i>) as an image of courting destruction reflects the architectural symbolism of the ancient city gate as the threshold of social aspiration and pride. The great gates of ancient cities (the Lion Gate at Mycenae, the gates of Babylon) communicated power and status. &#8220;Raising one&#8217;s gate&#8221; may refer either to literal architectural display of wealth (building an ostentatiously large house-gate) or the metaphorical sense of elevating one&#8217;s threshold of pride — both court destruction.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The connection between &#8220;crooked heart&#8221; and &#8220;perverse tongue&#8221; reflects the consistent Proverbs teaching that inner character expresses itself in speech. The ancient world generally understood speech as more than mere communication — words had binding force (oaths, blessings, curses were understood to carry real power; cf. Isaac&#8217;s irrevocable blessing of Jacob in Gen&#160;27). A perverse tongue was therefore doubly dangerous: it expressed corrupted character and set corrupted forces in motion.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The grief of a fool&#8217;s father was a recognized social reality in the ancient world where a son&#8217;s public conduct directly determined the family&#8217;s honor. In Mediterranean honor-shame culture, a foolish or disgraced son was not merely a personal disappointment but a public humiliation that affected the father&#8217;s standing in the community. The wisdom teacher&#8217;s appeal to the &#8220;my son&#8221; pupil consistently invokes this social dimension: becoming wise honors parents; foolishness shames them.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The joyful heart as &#8220;good medicine&#8221; (<i>yêtîb gēhāh</i>) reflects ancient Mediterranean understandings of the connection between emotional state and bodily health — what modern medicine calls psychosomatic medicine. Galen and Hippocrates both recognized that mental states affected physical health; the Hebrew tradition embedded this observation in wisdom literature. The &#8220;crushed spirit&#8221; (<i>rûaḥ nĕkēʾāh</i>) that dries up the bones describes depression as a physiological as well as psychological condition.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Secret bribery in the legal process was both widely practiced and widely condemned across the ancient Near East. Hammurabi&#8217;s Law Code included provisions against judicial bribery. In Israel, the gate-court system was vulnerable to corruption precisely because it operated without professional judges or formal procedures — the elders who sat in the gate were susceptible to social pressure and inducements. Amos&#8217; accusation that the poor are sold &#8220;for a pair of sandals&#8221; (Amos&#160;2:6) reflects the lived reality of judicial corruption.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The contrast between the wise person whose eyes are fixed on Wisdom that is &#8220;right in front of&#8221; them, and the fool whose eyes &#8220;wander to the ends of the earth,&#8221; captures the ancient problem of attention and focus. Wisdom was not an esoteric secret to be discovered in distant places (cf. Bar&#160;3:29-30 — wisdom is not &#8220;in the heavens, who will go up to get it?&#8221;; Deut&#160;30:12-14 — the word is not in heaven). The fool seeks what is near everywhere except where it is.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The parent-child grief dynamic (foolish son = grief to father, bitterness to mother) was socially acute in the ancient world for the reasons of honor-shame dynamics already noted at v21. The specific gendering here — grief to <i>father</i>, bitterness to <i>mother</i> — may reflect the different relational textures: the father bears the public honor-cost; the mother bears the more intimate emotional cost of her child&#8217;s failure. The double mention (v21 and v25) emphasizes that a child&#8217;s wisdom or folly is never merely a personal matter.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The protection of the innocent from judicial punishment was a fundamental principle of ANE law codes. Hammurabi&#8217;s prologue declares his purpose: &#8220;to prevent the strong from oppressing the weak, to see that justice is done to the orphan and the widow.&#8221; The specific mention of &#8220;striking the noble for acting rightly&#8221; reflects a recognized corruption: punishing people for doing what they should do, simply because they have acted in ways that offend those in power.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The virtue of restrained speech — few words, calm spirit — was prized in ancient wisdom across cultures. Egyptian instruction literature: &#8220;He who weighs his words does not stumble; he who speaks without restraint ends in trouble.&#8221; The calm spirit (<i>qar-rûaḥ</i>, cool of spirit) contrasts with the hot-tempered fool of 14:17, 29 whose heated spirit (hot nose = anger) produces hasty and destructive speech. Temperature-of-spirit was a recognized indicator of wisdom in the ancient world.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The observation that even a fool who stays silent is considered wise is a practical insight into social epistemology: others can only judge you by what you say and do. The fool who says nothing provides no evidence of folly. This is not a commendation of silence-as-deception but an observation about the social construction of reputation. In the honor culture of the ancient world, reputation was constructed through public performance — the fool who withholds public performance withholds the evidence of his folly.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>The warning against the isolationist who &#8220;pursues his own desires&#8221; reflects the ancient communal ethic in which the individual self was always embedded in family, clan, and community. The isolated individual in the ancient world was a social anomaly — either a rebel, an outcast, or someone who had severed the kinship bonds that constituted normal social existence. The &#8220;sound wisdom&#8221; (<i>kol-tûšiyyāh</i>) that the isolationist defies is not merely personal prudence but the accumulated communal wisdom embodied in the social fabric.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The fool who takes no pleasure in understanding but only in &#8220;self-expression&#8221; (<i>bĕhitgallôt libbô</i>, the exposing/revealing of his heart) describes a recognizable social type: the person who enters conversations not to learn but to display. In the ancient pedagogical context of wisdom transmission — where learning required listening, submission to the teacher, and the controlled disclosure of one&#8217;s views — the opposite disposition was the definitive mark of the unteachable fool.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The pairing of wickedness with contempt (<i>qālôn</i>) and disgrace with reproach reflects the honor-shame social logic: moral failure attracts social shame in the ancient world not because communities were moralistic but because honor was the primary social currency. Wickedness, once detected, destroyed the reputation that enabled participation in commerce, legal recourse, and community life. The sequence wickedness → contempt → disgrace → reproach describes a cascade of social consequences.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The &#8220;deep waters&#8221; (<i>mayim ʿămûqîm</i>) as a metaphor for the words of a person&#8217;s mouth appears also in 20:5: &#8220;The purposes of a person&#8217;s heart are deep waters.&#8221; Deep water in the ancient world was both a resource (wells, cisterns) and a danger (the primordial deep, chaos-waters). The image captures the ambiguity of speech: it can be profound and nourishing (the wisdom-fountain stream) or dangerously obscure and unfathomable.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Partiality to the wicked in judicial proceedings was a specific violation of the Mosaic judicial code (Deut&#160;16:19: &#8220;You shall not pervert justice; you shall not show partiality&#8221;). The connection between the wicked person&#8217;s advantage and the righteous person&#8217;s deprivation of justice reflects the zero-sum character of ancient legal proceedings: acquitting the undeserving meant condemning or ignoring the deserving. The gate-court that honored social position over covenant law was a standing target of prophetic criticism (Amos&#160;5:10-12).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The fool whose lips &#8220;walk him into arguments&#8221; reflects the ancient understanding that uncontrolled speech created enmities that led to physical danger. In the honor-shame culture where verbal insults required vindication through counter-insult or physical retaliation, the fool&#8217;s unguarded mouth was a genuinely dangerous liability. The escalation from argument to &#8220;calling out for a beating&#8221; describes the social logic of the spiral: each exchange of insults heightened the demand for physical resolution.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The repetition and intensification from v6 to v7 — the fool&#8217;s mouth as ruin, his lips as a trap for his very life — captures the ancient wisdom tradition&#8217;s consistent theme that speech is the arena of greatest danger for the undisciplined person. The &#8220;trap for his life&#8221; (<i>môqēš napšô</i>) echoes the net-and-trap imagery of the Strange Woman in Prov&#160;7 and the hunter metaphors throughout: the fool hunts others with his words but traps himself.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Gossip described as &#8220;choice morsels&#8221; (<i>mitlahamîm</i>, delicacies/swallowed eagerly) that &#8220;sink down into the inner depths&#8221; is one of Proverbs&#8217; most psychologically acute observations. The pleasure of gossip was recognized — people eagerly consume and repeat it — but the deeper danger is its permeation: it sinks into the <i>ḥadrê bāṭen</i> (inner chambers of the belly), lodging in memory and shaping perception in ways that cannot be easily recalled. The same saying appears at 26:22.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The equation of laziness and destruction reflects the ancient agrarian economy&#8217;s zero-tolerance for sloth. In subsistence agriculture, failure to work at the right moment — not plowing at the right time, not harvesting before rain — meant food insecurity. The comparison of the lazy worker to &#8220;the one who destroys&#8221; (<i>baʿal mašḥît</i>) is not hyperbole but economic reality: insufficient labor produces the same outcome as deliberate sabotage. The economic context gives the moral claim its force.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The strong tower (<i>migdal ʿōz</i>) of YHWH&#8217;s name is one of the most vivid architectural metaphors in Proverbs. Ancient cities were defined by their towers — the thick-walled refuge towers to which civilians fled during attack. The name of YHWH as such a tower invokes the ancient institution of asylum in sacred spaces: temples were recognized asylum zones in the ancient world where the threatened could &#8220;run to&#8221; and be under divine protection. V11 immediately contrasts this with the false tower of the rich man&#8217;s wealth — imagined rather than real.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The rich man&#8217;s wealth as a &#8220;strong city&#8221; and &#8220;high wall in his imagination&#8221; (<i>bĕmaśkîtô</i>) deliberately echoes and contrasts with v10. The fortified city was the supreme ancient security concept — massive walls, stored provisions, garrison troops. Wealth creates the subjective experience of being in such a city; v11&#8217;s qualifier &#8220;in his imagination&#8221; is the commentary on v10: the true strong tower is YHWH&#8217;s name; the wealth-tower exists only as self-deception.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The pride/destruction (v18:12 = v16:18 = v11:2) sequence is among Proverbs&#8217; most consistent theological patterns. The specific formulation here — pride before destruction, humility before honor — has a temporal structure: humility <i>precedes</i> the honor that comes as a gift; pride <i>precedes</i> the destruction that comes as a consequence. This temporal structure is essential: humility is not rewarded as behavior but recognized as the prior condition of the honor-gift, just as pride is recognized as the precondition of the judgment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The warning against answering before listening reflects the ancient judicial and deliberative ideal of patient examination before judgment. The Mosaic law required witnesses and careful investigation before any verdict (Deut&#160;19:15-19; Num&#160;35:30). The fool who pronounces before listening imitates the corrupt judge who has made up his mind before hearing the case — both produce the same result: &#8220;folly and disgrace.&#8221; Sirach 11:7-8 makes the same point explicitly: &#8220;Do not find fault before you investigate.&#8221;</p>",
    "14": "<p>The resilience of the human spirit (<i>rûaḥ</i>) against bodily sickness versus the un-bearability of a crushed spirit reflects ancient Israelite anthropology in which the spirit/breath was the animating force that could maintain bodily function despite illness. The &#8220;crushed spirit&#8221; — the experience of profound loss of will or hope — was understood to be more devastating than physical illness because it removed the animating force itself. The therapeutic tradition of the Psalms of lament functioned as the ancient community&#8217;s resource for the crushed spirit.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The picture of the discerning heart that &#8220;acquires&#8221; (<i>qānāh</i>) knowledge and the wise ear that &#8220;seeks&#8221; it reflects the proactive posture toward learning that Proverbs consistently commends. In the ancient scribal tradition, wisdom was transmitted through formal relationships requiring active seeking — the student had to pursue the teacher, not merely wait for wisdom to arrive. The same vocabulary of acquiring/seeking appears in 4:5,7 (acquire wisdom, acquire understanding) and 8:17 (those who seek me find me).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The &#8220;gift&#8221; (<i>mattān</i>) that opens doors and brings one before important people reflects the ancient gift-economy that governed access to power. In the patron-client system that structured ancient Mediterranean and Near Eastern society, access to powerful persons required the mediation of gifts — not primarily as bribes (cf. v23:1-3 which distinguishes gift-bringing from bribery in court) but as the tokens of relationship that established one as a participant in the exchange network. Joseph&#8217;s brothers bringing gifts to Egypt (Gen&#160;43:11) and Abigail&#8217;s gift to David (1&#160;Sam&#160;25:18-19) illustrate the social necessity of gift-giving.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The observation that &#8220;the first to state his case seems right, until another comes and examines him&#8221; reflects the ancient adversarial legal tradition. In Israelite gate-court proceedings, each party presented their case in turn; the Deuteronomic requirement for two or three witnesses (Deut&#160;19:15) recognized that uncontested testimony was inherently one-sided. The wisdom here is essentially procedural: suspend judgment until cross-examination has occurred. Sirach 11:7-8 extends this to interpersonal judgment generally.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Lot-casting to settle disputes and part the mighty from each other reflects the widespread ancient use of sacred lots as the final arbiter in conflicts that human wisdom could not resolve. The Urim and Thummim (Exod&#160;28:30; Num&#160;27:21; 1&#160;Sam&#160;14:41-42) were Israel&#8217;s sacred lots, carried by the high priest for exactly such decisions. The application to disputes &#8220;between the mighty&#8221; is significant: when social equals clashed and no one had authority to impose a decision, the lot provided a divine verdict that all parties could accept.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The fortified-city metaphor for a brother who has been offended reflects ancient siege-warfare experience. A breached city could be stormed; a fortified city could resist siege for years (Samaria held out against Assyria for three years, 2&#160;Kings&#160;17:5). The point is the near-impossibility of reconciliation once a breach has occurred — relational fortifications are erected that are harder to penetrate than military ones. &#8220;Disputes between brothers are like the bars of a citadel&#8221; — the internal reinforcing bars that prevented gates from being forced open.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The agricultural metaphors of fruit and produce applied to speech (&#8220;satisfied by the fruit of his words,&#8221; &#8220;filled by the produce of his lips&#8221;) reflect the ancient understanding that words — like fields — have a harvest. In a culture where the fruit of one&#8217;s labor was the primary measure of prosperity, applying crop-metaphors to speech was a way of insisting that words have real, tangible consequences. You will eat what you grow with your speech — for good or ill.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;Death and life are in the power of the tongue&#8221; is among the most sweeping statements about speech in the Hebrew Bible. The ancient world took this literally in ways moderns often do not: blessings and curses were understood to have real power (Isaac&#8217;s blessing in Gen&#160;27 was irrevocable; Balaam&#8217;s curse in Num&#160;22-24 was feared as genuinely dangerous). Proverbs&#8217; wisdom tradition demythologizes this slightly — it is the social and relational consequences of speech that constitute its death-and-life power — but the claim remains radical: every speech act has ultimate stakes.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Finding a wife as receiving &#8220;favor from the LORD&#8221; frames marriage within the covenant-blessing framework: a good wife is not merely a social acquisition but a divine gift. The institution of marriage in the ancient world was primarily a social and economic arrangement between families — the betrothal was a legal contract; the wedding was its public celebration. Within this transactional framework, Proverbs insists on a theological dimension: the woman who is truly <i>ʾēšet ḥayil</i> (woman of valor, 31:10) is a gift from YHWH that transcends the social arrangement.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The socioeconomic contrast — the poor person speaks with pleas; the rich person answers harshly — describes the power differential that governed ancient social interaction. The poor had no leverage except appeal; the wealthy had the social position to set terms. The observation is sociological rather than prescriptive: this is how the world works. The implicit critique is that harshness toward the poor contradicts YHWH&#8217;s stated concern for the poor (Deut&#160;15:7-11; Lev&#160;19:9-10) and will not go ultimately unaddressed (19:17; 22:22-23).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The distinction between &#8220;companions who lead to ruin&#8221; and &#8220;a friend who sticks closer than a brother&#8221; invokes the institution of covenant friendship (<i>berît</i>) that created family-like bonds of total loyalty between non-kin. The word <i>rēʿa</i> (companion/neighbor) covers a range from casual acquaintance to intimate friend; the qualifying phrase &#8220;sticks closer than a brother&#8221; identifies the covenant-friend who has sworn loyalty that exceeds even family obligation. The David-Jonathan covenant and the Ruth-Naomi bond are the narrative paradigms.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(c, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', c)
    total = sum(len(vs) for vs in PROVERBS.values())
    print(f'proverbs mkt-context: {total} entries written (ch16-18)')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
